#:blog{:title "All Money Is Monopoly Money",
       :date #inst "2025-11-20T00:00:00.000-00:00",
       :abstract
       [:p
        "People love to argue about what counts as \"real money.\" Bitcoin advocates say government currencies "
        "are doomed because they can be printed. Fiat advocates say Bitcoin is a speculative token detached from "
        "the real economy. But both sides miss a fundamental point: all money (BTC, USD, gold tokens, Rai stones) is "
        "Monopoly money. Its value comes from trust, which enables coordination, not from the material itself."],
       :content
       [:section.blog-article
        [:div.section-inner
         [:article
          :$blog-title
          :$blog-date

          [:p
           "People love to argue about what counts as \"real money.\" Bitcoin advocates say government currencies "
           "are doomed because they can be printed. Fiat advocates say Bitcoin is a speculative token detached from "
           "the real economy."]

          [:p "But both sides miss a fundamental point, one powerfully argued by anthropologist David Graeber in "
           [:a {:href "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Debt:_The_First_5,000_Years"} [:em "Debt: The First 5,000 Years"]]
           ": money did not emerge from barter. It emerged from " [:strong "debt"] "."]

          [:p
           [:strong "All money (BTC, USD, gold, clam shells) is Monopoly" [:sup.footnote-marker " [1]"] " money."]
           " It is a social construct, a system of accounting for obligations. Its value comes from "
           [:strong "trust"]
           " that these obligations will be honored, not from the material itself."]

          [:p
           "Without trust that others will accept your tokens, they become worthless, no matter what backs them. "
           "To understand why, we must separate two things:"]

          [:ul.bulleted
           [:li [:strong "Accounting assets"] " (claims, debts, IOUs)"]
           [:li [:strong "Real assets"] " (actual goods and services)"]]

          [:h2 "1. Money as Debt: The Accounting Layer"]

          [:p
           "The standard story of money's origin is a myth. Barter, we are told, was too inefficient, so humanity invented "
           "coins. As David Graeber meticulously documented, this is backwards. For thousands of years before coins were ever minted, human economies were built on credit in the form of informal IOUs and social obligations."]

          [:p
           "A village farmer didn't barter for his neighbor's boots; he'd simply say, \"I owe you one.\" "
           "These debts were flexible, social, and embedded in a web of mutual aid. This is what Graeber calls "
           "\"everyday communism,\" the baseline of human cooperation."]

          [:p
           "What we call money today (whether it's dollars in a bank, BTC on a ledger, or an entry in an Excel sheet) is "
           "just a formal, impersonal system for tracking these claims and debts. They are accounting artifacts, "
           "not physical resources."]

          [:ul.bulleted
           [:li "A dollar is an IOU from the US government (the debtor) to the private sector and other governments (the creditors)."]
           [:li "A Bitcoin is a cryptographically secured entry in a public ledger. This is its technical implementation, but not its economic essence. Fundamentally, like all forms of money, it represents an accounting relationship: one person's credit is another's debit, always balancing to zero."]
           [:li "Neither feeds anyone or builds anything on its own."]]

          [:p
           "This reveals the iron law of accounting that governs all money: " [:code "credit + debit = 0"] ". "
           "For every asset in the system, there is a corresponding liability. As the saying goes, " [:strong "one person's debt is another person's asset"] ". "
           "Your bank account is your asset, but it is the bank's liability. The entire global financial system is a web of these interlocking IOUs, and the net balance is always, and must always be, zero."]

          [:p
           [:strong "Money turns real only when it flows through people doing work."]
           " Until then, it's just a number."]

          [:p
           "The conversion of Monopoly money into something of value only happens when it flows through people "
           "creating goods and services, just like the flow of entropy from low to high only generates work when "
           "it flows through a turbine."]

          [:p
           "This is the remarkable achievement of money: it allows "
           [:strong "accounting abstractions to be used as if they were real physical commodities"]
           ". But this transformation is not automatic; it only becomes possible when money flows among people "
           "creating real goods and services. The abstraction becomes \"real\" through productive flow."]

          [:p "Without flow, money is static potential energy: stored, inert, idle."]

          [:h2 "2. From Social Debt to State-Enforced Money"]

          [:p "If early economies ran on informal, social debt, where did coins and cash come from? Graeber's answer is violence. "
           "Impersonal, state-issued money wasn't invented for trade. It was invented to pay soldiers."]

          [:p
           "Ancient empires created what Graeber calls the \"military-coinage-slavery complex.\" A king needed to provision "
           "his army. He would stamp his seal on bits of metal, declare them valuable, and pay his soldiers. "
           "To ensure the coins were accepted, he would then demand them back as taxes. Suddenly, everyone "
           "in the kingdom needed to get their hands on the king's currency, creating a market."]

          [:p
           "This is the brutal origin of physical money. It was a tool to rip economies out of their local, trust-based "
           "credit systems and reorient them around the state's military needs. This is also the historical root of "
           "Modern Monetary Theory (MMT):"]

          [:p [:strong "All new state money enters the economy through government spending."]]

          [:ul.bulleted
           [:li "Taxes destroy money."]
           [:li "Borrowing delays destruction."]
           [:li "Spending creates money."]]

          [:h3 "The Waterfall Analogy"]

          [:p "Taxation and spending are the two poles of a battery that powers the economy. Government spending injects potential (money) into the system, and taxation removes it. This differential doesn't just fund services; it creates a fundamental " [:strong "entropy gradient"] " that compels money to flow, enabling economic work to be done, much like a dam creates a pressure gradient for water."]

          [:p "This is why the " [:strong "flow"] " of government money matters most, often more than the initial spending's perceived efficiency. The ultimate effectiveness of that flow reduces to the quality of a " [:strong "human capital"] " it moves through: how educated and knowledgeable are the people who receive and circulate it?"]
        
          [:p "A strong flow through a skilled population creates a recursive feedback loop. An 'inefficiently' spent dollar that enters this cycle can trigger a cascade of transactions and create immense real wealth. This recursive process generates new entropy gradients for further work; every recursion through this process has the potential to create more entropy gradients and amplify real wealth in the form of goods and services. It's analogous to a fractal cell wall: a flat wall cannot make use of ambient heat, but the fractal structure creates entropy gradients, pockets of order from chaos, that a " [:a {:href "/blog/maxwells-demon-economic-value.blog"} "Maxwell's demon"] " could use to perform work."]
        
          [:p "Because of this recursive, fractal effect, the initial spending's efficiency matters far less than the quality of the human network that propagates the flow. The human capital is the critical factor. A 'well-spent' dollar that flows to unskilled and unknowledgable human capital creates nothing, as the productive cycle cannot begin."]

          [:p "Fiat currencies, through the cycle of government spending and taxation, create a " [:strong "structural entropy gradient"] " that powers economic activity. Bitcoin has no such native mechanism. It is not spent into existence to build infrastructure or fund services."]
          [:p "So where does Bitcoin's "flow" come from? It is not from a productive cycle, but from a psychological one: " [:strong "speculation"] ". The primary force moving Bitcoin is the collective belief that its price will rise or fall. This creates a gradient, but it is a gradient of market sentiment, not of underlying economic work. This speculative gradient is not just noise; it creates another kind of entropy gradient that serves a specific function: a fiat money transfer protocol. While technologically subpar for this task compared to other blockchains (like Algorand, on which ShiBi is built), Bitcoin's massive speculative gradient gives it a power and reach that technically superior systems lack. This usefulness as a money transfer vehicle, driven by speculation, generates its own native demand, producing a distinct entropy gradient."]
          [:p "Even with this native demand, Bitcoin remains a derivative system. It must " [:strong "piggyback"] " on the very fiat systems it purports to replace. To be converted into real goods and services, Bitcoin must tap into the economic flows and trust networks that fiat systems, powered by taxation and public spending, have already built. It relies on fiat's river to have any current at all, even as it creates its own channel alongside it."]]

          [:h3 "The National Debt Paradox"]
          [:p
           "This framework flips the script on the U.S. national debt. The media often portrays it as a scary, household-style debt that must be repaid. But this is a fundamental misunderstanding. If government spending creates money and taxation destroys it, what does 'paying off the debt' actually mean?"]
          [:p
           "It means destroying U.S. dollars. The national debt is simply the total sum of dollars the government has spent into the economy that it has not yet taxed back. These dollars are held as assets (savings) by the private sector and other countries. For the U.S. to 'pay down its debt,' it would have to tax more dollars out of the economy than it spends in. This would effectively " [:strong "burn USD"] ". Since the dollar is the world's reserve currency, this would drain global liquidity and could cause " [:strong "world trade to crash"] "."]
          [:p
           "This reveals a deeper truth: some debts are not meant to be repaid. Their purpose is to define and sustain a relationship, not to be settled. Think of the 'debt' a child owes their parents; it represents a lifelong bond of gratitude and obligation. To speak of 'repaying' it is to fundamentally misunderstand the relationship, and attempting to do so would only damage it. The U.S. national debt functions in precisely the same way on a global scale. It is the foundational IOU that underpins the entire world's financial system. It is not a household debt to be eliminated, but a permanent, relational bond. To 'repay' it would mean destroying the very economic relationships that enable global trade, causing the world economy to collapse."]

          [:h2 "3. Why Bitcoin Supporters Distrust Fiat"]

          [:p
           "Bitcoin advocates have legitimate critiques of fiat currency:"]

          [:ul.bulleted
           [:li "Governments can print money at will"]
           [:li "This dilutes the value of existing holdings"]
           [:li "Political decisions, not economic logic, drive monetary policy"]
           [:li "Inflation acts as a hidden tax on savers"]
           [:li "The system privileges those closest to the money printer"]]

          [:p
           "These concerns are real. But they mistake the "
           [:strong "abuse of a system"]
           " for a fundamental flaw in how value coordination works."]

          [:h3 "The Bitcoin Alternative: Fixed Supply"]

          [:p
           "Bitcoin treats money like a commodity with fixed supply. But "
           [:strong "money isn't wealth; it's a coordination tool"]
           " to mobilize human skill and creativity."]

          [:p "A fixed monetary supply assumes:"]

          [:ul.bulleted
           [:li "resources are fixed"]
           [:li "opportunities are fixed"]
           [:li "innovation doesn't require new liquidity"]
           [:li "economies grow linearly"]]

          [:p
           "This worldview is pre-industrial, pre-knowledge, and fundamentally mismatched with modern innovation "
           "economies."]

          [:p
           "A fixed supply of BTC is like a CPU locked to one thread even though the hardware can run 32 threads "
           "in parallel. "
           [:strong "Scarcity doesn't create stability; it throttles the ability of a society to scale."]]

          [:p
           "BTC does not solve scarcity. It simply enforces artificial scarcity."]

          [:h3 "The Real Issue: Flow, Not Supply"]

          [:p
           "Bitcoin maximalists think scarcity equals value, but this is a profound misunderstanding. Scarcity without productive flow is just hoarding. Money isn't valuable because it's scarce; it's valuable because it " [:strong "moves"] ". It is the very motion of money through an economy of skilled people that " [:em "causes"] " real goods and services to be created."]

          [:p
           "The problem with fiat isn't that governments can create it. The problem is "
           [:em "where"]
           " that money enters the economy and "
           [:em "how"]
           " it flows afterward."]

          [:h2 "4. Savings, Investment, and the Illusion of \"Hard Value\""]

          [:p "All saving is delayed consumption."]

          [:p
           "You store your Monopoly money because you believe other people will turn it into real productive "
           "value in the future. "
           [:strong "Investment is delayed consumption"]
           " because you believe the flow of money through other people has the potential to create more goods "
           "and services, which you have a claim on because you delayed present consumption."]

          [:h3 "The Problem of Concentration"]

          [:p "If the rich accumulate too much of the flow:"]

          [:ul.bulleted
           [:li "money velocity slows"]
           [:li "production slows"]
           [:li "innovation slows"]
           [:li "consumption slows"]]

          [:p "This is not a moral argument. It's physics. High concentration dampens the gradient."]

          [:p
           "When buying power is concentrated in the few, the flow of money slows down, which also slows down "
           "the creation of goods and services and consumption."]

          [:p
           "To be fair, rich people don't leave their money in cash; they invest it. This is why it's so hard to"
           "tax rich people: taxation happens only when they transform their assets into cash. If they invest in "
           "nonproductive assets, all it does is drive up prices."]

          [:p
           "Even BTC whales face this: if early holders keep hoarding, Bitcoin cannot circulate enough to become "
           "a general medium of exchange. The system behaves like a lake with no outflow, not a river."]

          [:h2 "5. BTC and USD Are Both Monopoly Money: Just in Different Games"]

          [:p "USD is Monopoly money backed by:"]

          [:ul.bulleted
           [:li "government spending"]
           [:li "taxation power"]
           [:li "legal system"]
           [:li "economic output"]
           [:li "institutional inertia"]
           [:li "social trust"]]

          [:p "BTC is Monopoly money backed by:"]

          [:ul.bulleted
           [:li "node consensus"]
           [:li "cryptography"]
           [:li "protocol rules"]
           [:li "miner incentives"]
           [:li "speculative belief"]
           [:li "community trust"]]

          [:p
           "One is a political coordination game. The other is a computational coordination game."]

          [:p [:strong "Neither is \"more real\" than the other."]]

          [:p
           "What matters is not the token but the "
           [:strong "trust"]
           " that enables coordination. Value emerges from "
           [:strong "how money flows"]
           ", not from what money is."]

          [:h2 "6. Money as an Entropy Gradient"]

          [:p "We can reframe money as:"]

          [:ul.bulleted
           [:li "a flow"]
           [:li "a signal"]
           [:li "an attention gradient"]
           [:li "an economic coordination protocol"]]

          [:p "Not as a store of \"objective\" value."]

          [:ul.bulleted
           [:li "BTC tries to freeze value (fixed supply of 21 million coins)."]
           [:li "USD tries to adapt value (flexible supply, interest rate controls, responsive to economic activity)."]
           [:li "ShiBi tries to expose value (local subjective pricing, no global supply constraints)."]]

          [:p
           "But in all three, money is still symbolic: a shared hallucination fueled by collective interpretation."]

          [:h2 "7. The Only Real Economy Is Human Work"]

          [:p
           "Strip everything away (BTC, USD, DeFi, central banks, miners, wallets) and what's left?"]

          [:ul.bulleted
           [:li "people growing food"]
           [:li "people building houses"]
           [:li "people writing code"]
           [:li "people designing chips"]
           [:li "people providing care"]]

          [:p [:strong "That is the real economy."]]

          [:p "Everything else is bookkeeping."]

          [:p
           "The mistake BTC solves isn't inflation. The mistake BTC makes is treating money as a commodity: "
           "confusing the bookkeeping layer (tokens) with the production layer (real goods and services)."]

          [:p
           "Money's remarkable achievement is that it allows accounting abstractions to be used "
           [:em "as if"]
           " they were real physical commodities. But BTC takes this metaphor literally, treating the token itself "
           "as the treasure rather than as a coordination tool that only becomes valuable through productive flow."]

          [:p "Money is not treasure. Money is not energy. Money is not wealth."]

          [:p [:strong "Money is a routing protocol for human effort."]]

          [:h2 "Conclusion: The Real Debate"]

          [:p
           "Once you see this, BTC vs. USD stops being a moral battle. It becomes an engineering question:"]

          [:p
           [:strong "Which monetary system creates the best flow of human activity?"]]

          [:p "That's the real debate: not ideology, not maximalism, not memes."]

          [:p
           "Money's value doesn't come from scarcity, government backing, or cryptographic proof. It comes from "
           "the " [:strong "trust"] " that our collective debts and obligations will be honored. It is a tool to "
           "coordinate human effort."]

          [:p
           "The best monetary system is the one that maximizes productive flow while minimizing friction, hoarding, "
           "and destructive forms of debt. As Graeber reminds us, our current system is not the only possible one. "
           "History shows that when debt becomes too burdensome, societies have often resorted to mass "
           "forgiveness, a Jubilee, to restore balance."]

          [:p "The real question is not what money " [:em "is"] ", but what we want it " [:em "to be"] "."]

          [:p "Everything else is just accounting."]

          [:div.footnotes
           [:hr]
           [:ol
            [:li {:id "footnote-1"}
             "The term 'Monopoly money' is a direct reference to the colorful, valueless currency used in the Parker Brothers board game "
             [:em "Monopoly"]
             ". Its worth is confined entirely to the social construct of the game, making it a perfect metaphor for real-world money."]]]

